## Error handling

This project uses result objects instead of throwing exceptions in service functions. This is one valid approach — if your team prefers exceptions, remove this section and document your own pattern.

```typescript
// This project's approach: return a typed result, never throw to the caller
async function getUser(id: string): Promise<Result<User>> {
  try {
    const user = await db.user.findUnique({ where: { id } });
    if (!user) return { ok: false, error: "USER_NOT_FOUND" };
    return { ok: true, data: user };
  } catch (e) {
    return { ok: false, error: "INTERNAL_ERROR" };
  }
}
```

## Naming

| Thing | Convention | Example |
|-------|-----------|---------|
| Files | kebab-case | `user-profile.ts` |
| Functions | camelCase | `getUserById()` |
| Types/Interfaces | PascalCase | `UserProfile` |
| Constants | SCREAMING_SNAKE | `MAX_RETRY_COUNT` |

## Anti-patterns

- Never use `any`. Use `unknown` with a type guard instead.
- Never use `enum`. Use `as const` objects or union types.
